        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We request a total of 3.3-hour ALMA Cycle 2 observation at an angular resolution
of 0.13" in Band 7 to image the putative circumstellar disk and the outflow gas 
around the MYSO in S255 IR mm1. Assuming a LTE excitation condition of
100-300 K, molecular line emission at Band~7 will yield a signal-to-noise
ratio (SNR) that is at least equivalent to those at Band 9 and will be
far superior to those at Band 3 or 6 for a very compact source with a fixed
column density observed at the same angular resolution. The high angular
resolution in ALMA Cycle 2 is readily far better than the best angular 
resolution attainable by any existing arrays. It is also perfectly suited
for compact sources with angular scales of 3" or less as seen in our
previous SMA observations.

Table 1 lists the main molecular transitions that will be covered and focused
on. We utilize three basebands within the powerful ALMA correlator for
accessing those tracers/transitions while reserving one primarily for
continuum imaging. The dual polarization mode is used for better noise
performance. The spectral resolution of 0.21 km/s for C34S and 0.42 km/s for
CH3CN are well suited for resolving the disk kinematics, which are typically
3 km/s in width. The spectral resolution of 0.98 km/s for SiO and CO are
adequate for high velocity outflowing gas. The resoltioin of 1.7 km/s at the
continuum baseband is more than sufficent for identifying and removing
possible line contamination.

We demonstrate the sensitivity requirement based on previous observations
of S255 IR with the SMA in the C34S (6-5) transition. The integrated
intensity of C34S (6-5) transition, which has a critical density
of ~ 10^7cm^{-3}, is 4.5 Jy/Beam km/s, unresolved within a
2.7" by 2.6" beam. This gives rise to a mass of ~ 0.6 M_sun,
under the assumption of a gas temperature of 170 K at LTE and a nominal
fractional abundance of ~ 5~10^{-10}. The LTE condition would be
consistently satisfied by a geometrically thin disk of 0.4 M_sun
with a diameter of less than 2.5" (or 4000 AU at a distance of 1.6 kpc).
Given that the de-convolved C34S (6-5) and CH3CN emission have sizes
of &lt;= 1" and with the same (LTE and fractional abundance) assumption 
as well as disk parameters, the expected brightness temperature of C34S
(7-6)  will be at least 60~K. At the spectral resolution of 0.4 km/s,
the proposed observation with less than 2-hour on-source integration will
provide a SNR of 30 at the line peak, sufficient for determining the gas
kinematics in the disk. 

We note that self-calibration against continuum emission
is expected to be feasible given the expected continuum flux density
(&gt;= 1.0~Jy at ~ 0.2") and the available a priori source model
obtained from previous SMA observations.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
